@500000 = ~A Message from the Fiends~
@500001 = ~A MESSAGE FROM THE FIENDS
Weight: 0

It is just an ordinary sheet of paper with a few dried stains and some dark ink. The stains could be blood. A message has been written in shaky letters.

^0xff393ffc"Nameless One, I have heard that you are searching for answers to many troubling questions. I may be able to help you uncover parts of your distant past. I also have a task for you that, along with the information you seek, may prove to be very well paid. Meet me at the Smoldering Corpse Bar.

- Tergush'tekhn"^-~
@500002 = ~Stygian Ice Storm Bolts~
@500003 = ~STYGIAN ICE STORM BOLTS
Enchantment: +3
Damage: 2-5 (crushing)
Special Effects:
 5 magical cold damage on hit
Thac0: +1
Speed: 5
Weight: 0
Proficiency: Missiles
Can be used only by modrons.

These bolts are imbued with a portion of Stygian power. When they strike a target, the surrounding area freezes, making the bolts difficult to remove. The frost is so intense that it causes permanent tissue damage and may lead to necrosis. Even fiends would struggle to resist such a powerful force.~
@500004 = ~Earring of Cold Protection~
@500005 = ~EARRING OF COLD PROTECTION
 Special:
 +25% Resistance to Cold and Magical Cold
Weight: 0

Frostbite is temporary or permanent skin damage caused by exposure to low temperatures. It usually begins in the most vulnerable, exposed parts of the body, such as the ears, nose, cheeks, fingers, and toes. To protect this delicate auditory organ, a Sensate designed a pair of earrings to shield the ears from frostbite, along with the swelling and possible necrosis it can cause. With this protection, he could freely enjoy the soft murmurs and sharp whistles carried by the frigid winds of Cania. It is a pity, however, that the earrings offered no defense against the claws of the gelugons.~
@500006 = ~Bone Whistle~
@500007 = ~BONE WHISTLE
Invokes the spell "Improved Strength" once a day
Weight: 0

Historical records suggest that these whistles were first crafted in the Abyss so that explorers and traders descending from the gate-town of Plague-Mort to deeper layers of the plane would stand a chance against the lesser Tanar'ri. Sensible planewalkers know better than to venture too far, as the chaotic nature of demons makes the likelihood of returning even slimmer. Even so, one must be prepared for the most unpredictable dangers, even on the upper layers. Forewarned is forearmed.

This whistle temporarily increases the user's strength to levels that would otherwise be unattainable. What is troubling, however, is that creating such whistles required a blood sacrifice from a living creature. In recent years, these magical items have also been used successfully when traveling to other Lower Planes. Despite their usefulness, their creation continues to raise ethical concerns.~
@500008 = ~The Nameless One's Fireball~
@500009 = ~THE NAMELESS ONE'S FIREBALL
Damage: 1-3 (missile)
Damage: 2-8 (fire)
Speed: 5
Weight: 5
Proficiency: Fists
Action: Ranged Weapon
Usable only by mages.
Usable only by the Nameless One.

Ignus has not forgotten the suffering his master caused. You regained that memory through the severe and painful loss of both hands. Now you can wield the same power as your former student and unleash a volley of fireballs at your enemies.~
@500010 = ~Fiend's Eye~
@500011 = ~FIEND'S EYE
Special:
 +5% Fire resistance
 +5% Magical Fire resistance 
 +5% Gas resistance 
 +5% Cold resistance
 +5% Magical Cold resistance
Weight: 0
 
This eye once belonged to a fiend, though it does not matter what kind, as it was not known for anything remarkable. What matters to you is that placing it in your eye socket allows you to take advantage of its immunity.~
@500012 = ~Ring of Baator~
@500013 = ~OBSIDIAN RING
Weight: 0

This large ring is set with black obsidian. It does not appear to be designed specifically for men or women.~
@500014 = ~RING OF BAATOR
Special: 
 +33% Fire resistance
 +33% Magical Fire resistance 
 +33% Cold resistance
 +33% Magical Cold resistance 
 +33% Acid resistance
Weight: 0

This large ring is set with black obsidian. It was clearly owned by a high-ranking Baatezu. This likely influenced the ring's magical properties, which not only prevent it from slipping off a finger that is too small but also enhance the wearer's protection against hellish conditions.~
@500015 = ~Gemariel's Claws~
@500016 = ~GEMARIEL'S CLAWS
(Default Weapon) 
Damage: 1-8, piercing or slashing 
Enchantment: +1 
Speed: 1 
Weight: 0 
Proficiency: Fists

Abishai claws are razor-sharp, fast, and deadly, but above all, effective. They are the Gemariel's primary weapon, enhanced with a touch of Set's magic. What more could an Abishai of this kind want from life?~
@500017 = ~Shackles~
@500018 = ~SHACKLES
Weight: 10

These shackles were broken centuries ago. At first glance, they do not seem to be of any use, but there is something strange about them and something familiar as well.~
@500019 = ~FALL-FROM-GRACE'S SHACKLES OF FREEDOM
Invokes: "Call Lightning" once a day
Weight: 10

These are the shackles from Fall-from-Grace's former cell, where she endured torture at the hands of the baatezu. The torment is beyond description, but it left such a deep mark that it permanently altered her tanar'ri nature. Now these broken shackles remain an unwanted and painful reminder of the triumph of faith and experience that allowed her to outsmart her executioners and gave Grace the chance to gather knowledge in the subsequent planes.

"My mother was among the finest, seducing countless mortal men to their eternal damnation. She now dwells in the Abyss, selling her children into slavery.

She sold me to the baatezu, the blood enemies of the tanar'ri. I think she rather expected that they would kill me -- despite her knowledge of other subjects, she knows little of their culture and the delight they take in tormenting others.

Fortunately, the baatezu are a proud species. The thought a tanar'ri could best them at anything was something intolerable to them. So I challenged one of the proudest of the pit fiends to a contest of improvisation, and it was here that my tanar'ri heart allowed me to win the day. The tanar'ri are chaotic creatures, wild and unpredictable. The baatezu are more cunning fiends, with orderly hearts. They understand improvisation, but they are not among its best practitioners. And thus, I won my freedom."
- Fall-from-Grace~
@500020 = ~Goblet from the Rivergate Tavern~
@500021 = ~GOBLET FROM THE RIVERGATE TAVERN
Weight: 1

This dirty goblet is one of many similar ones found in the Rivergate Tavern. You are not sure what is special about them, but Brill seems to keep a close eye on them.~
@500022 = ~Goblet from the Rivergate Tavern~
@500023 = ~GOBLET FROM THE RIVERGATE TAVERN
Weight: 1

This dirty goblet you received from Brill is no different from the many others found at the Rivergate Tavern. However, it is said to allow you to bypass the portal that opens in the inn. You hope that is true...~
@500024 = ~The Key to Ikss'odes's Apartment~
@500025 = ~THE KEY TO IKSS'ODES'S APARTMENT
Weight: 0

This is the key to the apartment of Ikss'odes, the thief.~
@500026 = ~SOEGO THE DUSTMAN'S HOLY SYMBOL
Special:
 +2 to Dexterity
 -1 to Charisma
 +25% Stealth Skill
Weight: 1

This holy symbol once belonged to Soego the Dustman. It is made of heavy iron and is designed to wrap around the wearer's wrist with a series of small, tightly linked chains. The symbol itself resembles a screaming face.

It was recently stolen from Soego and eventually found its way to Fragile-Tail's shop.
~
@500027 = ~"The Planewalker's Grimoire"~
@500028 = ~"THE PLANEWALKER'S GRIMOIRE"
Weight: 2

This book looks as if it took a dozen years to create. A great deal of effort has clearly gone into its readability and carefully planned structure. When you open it, you see the title: "The Planewalker's Grimoire." The book appears to contain notes on various elements of the multiverse.~
@500029 = ~"The Plane Truth"~
@500030 = ~"THE PLANE TRUTH"
Weight: 1

Author: David "Zeb" Cook

This book explores various planar adventures and the conclusions drawn from them, organized into three parts:

1. Codifying Sigil 
Excerpts from the notebooks of Fallendor the Mage, covering the following topics: aleax (a formless instrument of divine discipline born from a grave act of transgression against the gods), the Pain Dictionaries owned by Ganeesh of Baator (containing descriptions of all existing types of suffering, sorted by bodily response), the Doomguard and other factions, the geography of Sigil according to the factol of the Guvners, questions about the reality of the multiverse, portals as described by Prespos of Iriaebor, and a description of the Lady of Pain.

2. A Journey to the Outlands
Excerpts from the unpublished journals of Ambran the Seeker, a Half-Elf paladin of Oghma's temple near the court of Azoun Obarskyr IV, King of Cormyr. These journals detail Ambran's travels from one gate-town to another, including the dangerous Ribcage near Baator and Automata near Mechanus. A key lesson emerges from these journeys: the closer one approaches the edges of the Outlands, the more the area begins to reflect the nature of the adjacent plane.

3. The Transformation
From the final journal of Ambran the Seeker, a former paladin who abandoned his god, name, and realm to remain in the Outlands. May Oghma forgive his guilt, and may King Azoun judge him with mercy.~
@500031 = ~"Fire and Dust"~
@500032 = ~"FIRE AND DUST"
Weight: 1

Author: James Alan Gardner

This book chronicles the adventures of the Sigillian painter Britlin Cavendish and a handful of his eccentric companions as they travel through the various planes of existence. It begins in Sigil, where Britlin, hired to paint a portrait, accidentally witnesses a bloody assassination.~
@500033 = ~"The Seafarer's Arch or Final Port-of-Call"~
@500034 = ~"THE SEAFARER'S ARCH OR FINAL PORT-OF-CALL"
Weight: 1

This book describes, in a factual manner, the Seafarer's Arch, also known as the Seafarer's Portal or Final Port-of-Call. The uniqueness of this structure is that the portal leads to different destinations depending on which key is used. It is large enough to transfer full ships. Most of the portals lead to locations in the Prime Material Plane, with one known exception.

- Arborea: Pelion, Amun-thys. Key: scarab. Note: no water at the destination, only sand. Returning may be difficult.

The following notes concern only destinations in the Prime Material Plane:
- Aebrynis: a waterfall in the kingdom of Cariele
- Athas, Silt Sea: Warning: lurking monstrosities
- Io's Bloody Isles: an archipelago inhabited primarily by dragons
- Krynn in Krynnspace: rapids below a canyon in the Khalkist Mountains. Natives call all planes outside their own the Abyss
- Mystara, Savage Coast: a world in an unknown crystal sphere, one of the seven Wonders of the Multiverse. Key: cinnabryl amulet
- Oerth in Greyspace: an oblong shoal of rocks in the Nyv Dyr. Home plane of the lich Vecna
- Ortho: the home plane of the Harmonium faction
- Rock of Bral, Wildspace: a settlement on an asteroid on the outer reaches of the Prime Material Plane
- Toril in Realmspace: a sewer pipe from the Underdark that spills into the Trackless Sea

The question remains: what would happen if someone carried all the keys at once? No one has tried and returned. For the cautious, however, spells exist to protect keys that are not meant to be used, either to prevent accidents or to avoid losing disposable keys.~
@500035 = ~"The Ditch - Of Sigil and the Sea"~
@500036 = ~"THE DITCH - OF SIGIL AND THE SEA"
Weight: 1

Author: William James Cuffe

Perhaps not everyone is aware of this, but Sigil has its own river. "River" may be too grand a term, but it is water as extraordinary as the City of Doors itself. The author of this guide invites you on an imaginary rafting trip down the Sigil Ditch.

The guide describes the most important locations along the fifteen-meter-wide drain that flows from the Great Forge in the Lower Ward. The most detailed descriptions include:
- Suicide Falls: an almost-waterfall where flowers called "the Last Kiss Blossom" grow
- The Bridge That Spans Worlds: considered one of the seven Wonders of the Multiverse by the Sensates, it contains a planar gateway beneath it, the Seafarer's Arch, which leads to many different destinations depending on the key you possess
- The Wreck of the Trade Consortium's ship from the Phlogiston and the nearby Knife in the River: a piece of metal said to be the remains of another ship destroyed by the wrath of the Lady of Pain
- The Taker's Lock: an artificial branch of the Ditch controlled by the Fated
- The Industrial Stitches: located next to the Great Foundry and controlled by the Godsmen. Named for their resemblance to stitches over a nasty wound, they are the main source of pollution in the area, provoking strong protests from the Rosebringers sect

The author also explores additional topics, including:
- Portal keys and the Keycloak spell, which protects against their accidental use
- Portal connections to Ortho, the native plane of Harmonium, the Rock of Bral in Wildspace, and the Blood Isles of Io
- Legends of Cassie, the Ditch Beast that prowls the murky waters~
@500037 = ~"The Day of Grace"~
@500038 = ~"THE DAY OF GRACE"
Weight: 1

Author: Monte Cook

This small book tells a heartwarming story about the celebration of the Day of Grace in Sigil, a holiday that marks the passing of another year. It recounts the tale of a girl who approached the Lady of Pain, and contrary to expectations, nothing tragic occurred. The girl smiled at the Lady of Pain and is said to have whispered something. The ruler of Sigil floated away on her path. She could have struck the girl down, but she did not. That was the grace shown by the Lady of Pain.

The event happened on the last day of the year, according to the Guvners' records, and it moved the residents of Sigil so deeply that the holiday was named for it, encouraging everyone to treat their neighbors with a little more kindness. Public executions, floggings, and other punishments are suspended on this day. It is said that violating this custom could draw the attention of the Lady.

Merchants hold temporary sales, and each faction celebrates in its own way. The Sensates invent new ways to show kindness every year, and the Hardheads, surprisingly, even organize a parade. On this day, violence is largely set aside.~
@500039 = ~The Analects of Sigil~
@500040 = ~THE ANALECTS OF SIGIL
Weight: 1

Author: David "Zeb" Cook

Analects are a selection of fragments or complete works by an author, accompanied by source notes. In this case, they present the confession of the late Handulus, a scholar of the third rank, as recorded by Jerak of the Mercykillers before appointed witnesses.

Handulus, accused of murdering Jeron, the factor of the Guvners, testifies calmly, bearing no grudge against the Mercykiller. He was once a member of the Fraternity of Order, so his matter-of-fact and composed presentation of the case should come as no surprise. According to him, he inflicted no direct harm on the alleged victim. Instead, he directed his research toward the citadels of the Inner Planes, which he learned about from the Grand Dictum and a page from the perilous Codex of Infinite Planes, knowing that this path would ultimately lead to Jeron's demise.

The truths Handulus discovered during his visits to the Citadels of Surrender caused him to change his beliefs enough to join the Bleak Cabal. However, he had not visited the last of the disturbing citadels. That final citadel was intended for Jeron.~
@500041 = ~The Seven Wonders of the Multiverse~
@500042 = ~THE SEVEN WONDERS OF THE MULTIVERSE
Weight: 1

This neglected copy of the book contains only four of the seven so-called Wonders of the Multiverse. The list was compiled by the Society of Sensation to describe a collection of the most wondrous, breathtaking, and memorable sights across all known planes, created by the more or less conscious actions of intelligent beings.

- The Bridge That Spans Worlds (Sigil, The Ditch)
A massive mithral-adamantite bridge built before the Great Upheaval, at least five centuries before the reign of Factol Hashkar, by the now-defunct Forgesmiths faction, likely the progenitors of the Believers of the Source. It is a key location for Sigil's trade with other planes due to the presence of the multiportal, the Seafarer's Arch. It is unknown which came first, the portal or the bridge, but the wonder's name derives from the connection to other worlds.

- The Great Library of Thoth (The Outlands, Thebestys by the Ma'at River)
The place where all known knowledge is stored. It is said that the answer to every question can be found here, if one only knows where to look.

- The Modron Cathedral (Mechanus, Regulus)
A towering structure that is much larger inside than it appears from the outside, with copings that disappear into darkness. The secrets hidden here are impossible to comprehend without going mad. Entry requires a pass from the Central Office of Processing and Requests and an escort of at least two pentadrones per person.

- The Hollow World of Mystara (Prime Material Plane)
An unusual world with an inner sun at its core. It is the source of remarkable magic in the kingdoms of Glantri and Alphatia. The Immortals treated this place as an archive to preserve civilizations and species that were on the brink of extinction.~
@500043 = ~Blue Eye Prosthesis~
@500044 = ~Philosopher's Eye~
@500045 = ~BLUE EYE PROSTHESIS
Weight: 0

This blue sphere resembles an eye. Its unusual color draws your attention, but given its origins, you wonder whether it is worth testing its capabilities.~
@500046 = ~PHILOSOPHER'S EYE
Special Effects:
+1 Wisdom
+1 Intelligence
-1 Dexterity
+50% Missile Resistance
Weight: 0

This magical eye prosthesis helps you grasp the numerous paradoxes that exist in the multiverse. For example, if an arrow that has traveled half its distance to its target can be said to occupy one-half of its length, and an arrow that has traveled three-quarters of its distance is at that exact point, can we claim it was at rest for even a brief moment? Can this process continue indefinitely? Is it possible for an object to remain at rest while still in motion? And how, to use the terminology of modron scientists, do such precise measurements affect the time evolution of a quantum system, causing wavefunction collapse, or in other words, decoherence? Considering these questions, does the infinite division of a path during constant observation make motion impossible?

This prosthesis accelerates thought processes, helping you understand the essence of such problems, though at the cost of physical heaviness. It also divides the path of any projectile aimed at you in half, effectively granting you partial resistance to attacks.~
@500047 = ~Entropy +2~
@500048 = ~ENTROPY +2
Damage: 1-6 +2, piercing
Enchanted: +2
Special:
 +3 Poison damage (Save vs Poison negates)
THAC0: +2
Speed: 1
Weight: 5
Proficiency: Edged
Unusable by Lawful characters
Unusable by Priests

This greensteel short sword is one of Haer'Dalis's favorite weapons, second only to his other blade, Chaos. It features a highly intricate, ornate handle. The accumulation of sharp edges is characteristic of Doomguard weapons. The sword can inflict additional poison damage if the target fails a Saving Throw. Because of its nature, it is unlikely that creatures of Law could wield it effectively.~
@500049 = ~Prod~
@500050 = ~PROD
Weight: 7

Prod is an imp who works with Tergush'tekhn and the fiends from the Smoldering Corpse Bar. He is not very popular in the area, so he hides from prying eyes in your bag. His small size allows him to fit inside without disturbing the rest of your belongings. 

Prod is a fairly ordinary-looking imp. His skin is grayish, and his his hunched, scrawny frame does not intimidate anyone. The membranes of his bat-like wings have probably seen better days. Some of the holes look fresh and are likely the work of Joseph and his men. Prod does not seem bothered by this, and you do not know whether his wings will heal. Nevertheless, the imp radiates enthusiasm for the upcoming journey.~
@500051 = ~A Vial of Karach~
@500052 = ~A VIAL OF KARACH
Weight: 0

It is a small vial, but the vivid, silvery, swirling material inside seems capable of expanding many times its size and bursting the delicate container at any moment.~
@500053 = ~Scroll of Fireball~
@500054 = ~SCROLL OF FIREBALL
Allows user to cast "Fireball"
Allows user to copy "Fireball" into Spell Book.
Level: 3 / Wizard
Range: 40 feet
Duration: Instant
Speed: 3
Area of effect: 15-ft. radius
Saving throw: 1/2
Weight: 0

May Kossuth have mercy on those from whom the fires of creation demand the return of their gift of life.

This spell, very popular on the Prime Material Plane, allows the mage to create a heated ball of flame directly in their hands. When launched at an enemy, it bursts into an explosion, harming not only the target but everyone nearby. For this reason, caution is advised when choosing a target.

A single Fireball deals 1-6 points of damage per mage level (maximum 6-60). A successful saving throw reduces the damage by half. The spell is so powerful for its level that history records the archmage Tenser's research into making it less destructive. For power is one thing, and effectiveness another. And fire follows its own rules.~
@500055 = ~Scroll of Horrid Wilting~
@500056 = ~SCROLL OF HORRID WILTING SPELL  
Allows user to cast "Horrid Wilting"
Allows user to copy "Horrid Wilting" into Spell Book.
Level: 8 / Wizard
Range: 40 feet
Duration: Instant
Speed: 8
Area of effect: 30 ft. cube
Saving throw: 1/2
Weight: 0

This devastating spell, born from the mad imagination of the elementalist necromancer Abi-Dalzim, known as the Father of Droughts, causes all water to evaporate from living creatures within its area of effect. Abi-Dalzim committed many atrocities in the name of Incabulos, the god of disease, drought, and nightmares, but the worst of these was the creation of this destructive spell, which withers all vegetation in the area and vaporizes groundwater.

All living creatures within the area of effect take 1-8 damage per caster level, up to a maximum of 25-200 damage.~
@500057 = ~Scroll of Disintegrate~
@500058 = ~SCROLL OF DISINTEGRATE
Allows user to cast "Disintegrate"
Allows user to copy "Disintegrate" into Spell Book.
Level: 6 / Wizard
Range: 40 feet
Duration: Instant
Speed: 6
Area of effect: 1 creature
Saving throw: Negates
Weight: 0

The decomposition of a whole into its fragments. The elimination of integrity. The dissolution into its prime elements. However you describe it, this spell produces the simplest and perhaps most powerful offensive effect that even a child can imagine: the opponent's body explodes spectacularly, leaving behind only dust. The transformation is immediate and irreversible.

This spell can be blocked by magic resistance or appropriate spell protection. While it may not be effective against more powerful enemies, it can easily eliminate weaker ones.~
@500059 = ~Scroll of Lower Resistance~
@500060 = ~SCROLL OF LOWER RESISTANCE
Allows user to cast "Lower resistance"
Allows user to copy "Lower resistance" into Spell Book.
Level: 5 / Wizard
Range: 30 feet
Duration: 5 seconds per level
Speed: 5
Area of effect: 1 creature
Saving throw: None
Weight: 0

Some mages cast spells blindly, trusting that one of them will hit. Others, however, prefer a more strategic approach, first lowering the target's resistances to deal more severe damage later.

Casting this spell reduces the target's magic resistance to a minimum. This allows you to completely penetrate the defenses of even the most powerful spellcasters.~
@500061 = ~Scroll of Wail of the Banshee~
@500062 = ~SCROLL OF WAIL OF THE BANSHEE
Allows user to cast "Wail of the Banshee"
Allows user to copy "Wail of the Banshee" into Spell Book.
Level: 9 / Wizard
Range: 0
Duration: Instant
Speed: 9
Area of effect: 15-ft. radius around the caster
Saving throw: Negates
Weight: 0

Banshees, meaning "women of the fairy mound," are also known as groaning spirits or wailing ghosts. They are cruel specters, said to have been evil elven women in life. Taking on a misty form, they drain energy from their surroundings, causing the plants beneath them to wither. To the common folk, they are omens of death. To planewalkers, they are a truly deadly threat.

With this terrifying spell, the caster can unleash a piercing scream from their own throat, audible up to 15 feet away. Anyone who hears it dies instantly unless they succeed on a saving throw versus death. The caster and their companions are immune to the wail.~
@500063 = ~Key to the Rat and Splat Backrooms~
@500064 = ~KEY TO THE RAT AND SPLAT BACKROOMS
Weight: 0

This key opens the door to the Rat and Splat Backrooms.~
@500065 = ~The Bottomless Fang of Manill~
@500066 = ~THE BOTTOMLESS FANG OF MANILL
Weight: 5

At first glance, the huge fang before you might seem to have belonged to one of the bloodthirsty fiends of the lower planes. In truth, it is quite different. This tooth was taken from the carcass of a Manill, an ancient astral whale (gentle creatures that glide majestically through the astral sea). Its yellowed enamel is crisscrossed with a grid of glowing runes in an unknown language. The runes were likely inscribed by whoever hollowed out the fang and placed a small portal inside it. You do not know where objects you throw into the portal go, yet simply thinking of them returns them safely to your hand. They retain only a faint scent of fish oil afterward.

The fang can be used to store many items inside it.~
@500067 = ~Fragile-Tail's Journal~
@500068 = ~FRAGILE-TAIL'S JOURNAL
Weight: 1

This journal belonged to a wererat thief named Fragile Tail. It is a tattered, palm-sized volume bound in scraps of mismatched leather, some gray and smooth like cured rat hide, others cracked and brown like scavenged human skin. Its corners are frayed, chewed, and stained with grime, as if it had been gnawed during moments of idle anxiety. A crude latch of bent wire keeps it shut, wrapped three times and twisted off-center, serving more to discourage prying than to protect its contents.~
@500069 = ~Golem Shard~
@500070 = ~GOLEM SHARD
Damage: 2-5 piercing
Enchanted: +2
THAC0: +2
Speed: 2
Weight: 1
Proficiency: Slashing Weapons
Cannot be used by Priests.

This is a shard you managed to chip from Lothar's stone golem. It may contain a fragment of its power. Someone with very specific needs would surely recognize its value. Ultimately, it can be used as a weapon.~
@500071 = ~Shina-Tsu-Hiko Milk~
@500072 = ~SHINA-TSU-HIKO MILK
Invokes: "Haste"
Weight: 1

Shina-Tsu-Hiko is a wind deity residing in Limbo, said to have been born from the breath of Izanagi the Creator himself. Shina-Tsu-Hiko has the power to control the winds, bringing both gentle rain and devastating storms. This drink does not literally originate from him, but it has been sanctified by his magnificent power.

The effect of this cloudy, white, slightly bitter drink on anyone who consumes it is remarkable. Your body feels light and swift, as if every movement is carried by a strong, refreshing wind. It is useful for henchmen who wish to wreak havoc, spellcasters who want to cast spells quickly, and rogues who need to change locations in an instant.

This potion doubles the drinker's speed and sharpens their reactions in combat. The effect lasts for five turns (1 hour).~
@500073 = ~Mystic Energy Globe Wand~
@500074 = ~MYSTIC ENERGY GLOBE WAND
Weight: 1

Wands are 1 1/4 feet long and slender. They can be made of ivory, bone, or wood and are usually tipped with a material such as metal, crystal, or stone. They are fragile and break easily, so they are often kept in protective cases.

Wands are powered by charges, with each use consuming one or more charges depending on the item. Once a wand runs out of charges, it can no longer be used or recharged.

STATISTICS:
This wand creates a mystical globe of magical energy that strikes its target for 2-8 points of damage, ignoring saving throws. It then explodes in a concussive blast that deals additional damage. The blast also deals 1d8 points of magic damage.~
@500075 = ~Needle and Thread~
@500076 = ~NEEDLE AND THREAD
Weight: 0

This is a spool of thread and a small bone needle. They look like they are meant for stitching wounds, whether in the living or the dead, but there is more to them than meets the eye.

The needle appears ordinary, yet it holds a hidden power. When you touch it, images seem to form in your mind. One image stands out above the rest: a haystack, her long-term prison, from which she was rescued by some forgotten, attentive hero. This needle is now an artifact, a living metaphor for a hidden treasure. It remains concealed even from the shopkeeper who sold it. Only a few can see it for what it truly is.~
@500077 = ~Scroll of Haste~
@500078 = ~SCROLL OF HASTE
Allows user to cast "Haste"
Allows user to copy "Haste" into Spell Book.
Level: 3 / Wizard
Range: 15 ft.
Duration: (5 seconds per level) + 15 seconds
Speed: 3
Area of Effect: 15-ft. radius
Saving Throw: None
Weight: 0

When cast, all affected creatures double their movement, gain +2 to initiative, and make one extra attack per round. For example, a creature that normally moves 6 and attacks once per round now moves 12 and attacks twice per round.

The spell affects all allied creatures within a 15-ft. radius centered on a point chosen by the caster at the moment of casting. Creatures leaving the area remain affected, while those entering after casting are not.

This spell does not stack with itself or similar magic. Spellcasting and other effects are unaffected. This spell also negates the effects of a Slow spell.~
@500079 = ~Xaositect Guidelines?~
@500080 = ~XAOSITECT GUIDELINES?
Weight: 0

This letter was written by a Xaositect. You do not know what it is about, but an inner voice tells you that this gibberish is some kind of guideline. Unfortunately, any attempt to make sense of it strains your mind in vain.

"I once ate five cats. The candy in the night mouth lit up. Fresh are the pots full of water, but snow digests grass. Can the snake not? And what fate rings in the winding recesses of two candles? Ask the stool, I will answer bravely... I drank it and white chalk. See."~
@500081 = ~Robe of the Vanquished~
@500082 = ~ROBE OF THE VANQUISHED
Properties:
 Protection against Cania's deadly cold.
 +1 AC
 +1 to Luck
 +5 to Lore
Weight: 5

The supernatural cold of Cania, with temperatures supposedly low enough to freeze even a fire giant's blood, instantly penetrates ordinary clothing. In these robes, you can detect the scent of ancient and powerful magic. It is familiar, yet so distant and forgotten that you cannot discern the type of spells it contains. When you put the robe on, you experience a mixture of pleasant sensations and an indescribable fear that rises from deep within your mind. It feels as if you are instinctively afraid of some primordial devilry.

Over the centuries, the robe has taken on the color of blood, and for good reason. To protect certain wearers from the supernatural cold of Cania, a few drops of their blood must be sprinkled on the robe.

Once worn, the robe becomes invisible.

Although it protects against death from hypothermia in Cania, it is not effective against ordinary cold or magical cold damage.~
@500083 = ~Necklace of Rats~
@500084 = ~NECKLACE OF RATS
Weight: 0

Created by a jeweler from The Styx Oarsman, this necklace demonstrates that even the most gruesome raw materials can be transformed into something beautiful by the skilled hands of a talented artist, at least by demonic standards. The tails of cranium rats are woven together in an intricate, syncretic pattern reminiscent of both the biological geometry of the Abyss and the multicultural, cyclical nature of the city at the center of the multiverse, Sigil.

In addition to being a spectacular work of art, the necklace serves as a key to a portal leading to a forgotten temple somewhere in the Ditch.~
@500085 = ~Unregistered Sensory Stone~
@500086 = ~UNREGISTERED SENSORY STONE
Weight: 2

Surprisingly, you have found some kind of sensory stone. Is it lost or unregistered?
It is dirty and battered, but still functional.~
@500087 = ~"Captive Dancer"~
@500088 = ~"CAPTIVE DANCER"
Weight: 1

C.S. Macat

The sultan of Aharaj cast a languid gaze over the newest acquisitions and sighed with contentment. The vizier had truly outdone himself, selecting only the finest specimens from the market.

In a neat row before the throne stood slaves of various races and genders bound for the harem, all young and beautiful beyond measure, clad only in chains and colorful shawls that emphasized their charms rather than concealing their modesty. Most lowered their gaze to the floor, out of shame, fear, or embarrassment at the grandeur of the court. Only one man did not avert his bright eyes when they met the sultan's. How intriguing. The sovereign examined him with renewed curiosity.

Pointed ears peeked out from his long blond hair. He was tall and lean, with prominent muscles, especially on his legs, hidden beneath pale skin. Was he a warrior? No, unlikely. An acrobat? A circus performer? A pattern of tattoos covering almost his entire body suggested a bohemian past.

"Turn around," ordered the sultan.

The man did not hesitate. He bowed as if accustomed to the attention and adoration of a crowd, obeying gracefully. The sultan marveled at the delicate black ink coiling around his torso and limbs. Some lines curved into abstract spirals, while others formed rough outlines of daggers, swords, and other hand weapons. Subtle arcs of wings were inked across his shoulder blades.

"Your tattoos. What do they mean?" asked the sultan.

"They draw attention when I perform on stage," he replied. His voice was deep and strong, with a warm timbre. "I used to earn my living as a dancer. I often used knives in my acts. I can–"

The sultan raised his hand. The young man fell silent. Either the vizier had trained the slaves well, or the dancer instinctively knew how to fulfill his master's expectations. And the knives he mentioned... Yes, he would be perfect.

"I do not care who you were or what you used to do," said the sultan. "Your past is irrelevant. From now on, you are my pleasure slave, my pet, my toy. You are alive only because I allow it. Do you understand?"

"Of course, Your Brightness. I am but a worthless speck of dust beneath your heel."

The sultan smiled. Perfect. The young man fit his preferred type like a glove: clever, compliant, beautiful. He would be even more beautiful when despair first filled his eyes, followed by emptiness as he realized there was no salvation for him. How pleasant it would be to destroy him.

"From now on, your name is Aotari, like all the other favorites before you."

"As you wish, Your Brightness."

"Excellent. Staff!" A few servants hidden in the shadows stood at attention, afraid even to breathe. "Wash and prepare him. In one hour, I want him ready in my chambers."

"Yes, Your Brightness!" the servants replied in unison. Under the guard's supervision, they led the man away. Before leaving, the dancer glanced over his shoulder at the sovereign, his eyes reflecting both uncertainty and hope.

The sultan could not wait to snuff out that spark of hope.  

* * * 

Exactly an hour later, the sultan lounged on his bed among the pillows, watching as the servants and guards vacated the bedroom. He and Aotari were alone. The dancer wore only his chains but seemed unconcerned. He waited calmly, his expression blank.

The sultan nodded, pleased. "Before we begin, know this: I do not know what you are thinking, Aotari, but my guards are stationed behind these walls. I only need to say one word, and they will rush in and slaughter you. Do not attempt to escape. The windows are open, but remember we are on the fourth floor, with marble stairs below. Do not do anything foolish. You are not foolish, are you, Aotari?"

"I am not, Your Brightness."

"I am glad. I will have so much fun with you. I think we will start with knives. I may not be a dancer like you, but I can be quite creative with them as well. First–"

"You do love the sound of your own voice, do you not?"

The sultan's eyes widened at the insolence. Aotari stared at him with cold defiance, so different from his previous deference, but it mattered little. Nobody interrupts the sovereign.

The brazen youth had to be taught respect. The sultan opened his mouth to call for the guards, but no sound left him. Surprised, he grasped his throat. He screamed, but it was in vain. He could not understand what was happening.

He raised a questioning gaze at the slave and realized, mortified, that the lines on his shoulders glowed subtly purple, forming a strange glyph.

"I am sure you are wondering what has happened," said the dancer casually. "I will not keep you in the dark. Runes from my homeland are hidden in my tattoos. They represent a foreign magic completely unknown here, so your sages could not detect them. That is why my order was chosen for this task. I am a living grimoire that walks the planes."

The young man's stance and expression had completely changed. He resembled a cobra, a deadly predator ready to strike. Not out of hatred, but because it was his nature.

"We do not have much time, but courtesy and my code require that you at least understand why I am here, fulfilling this contract. Sultan of Aharaj, you will die today by my hand because your firstborn son grew tired of waiting for your demise. He paid a fortune to hasten your permanent abdication. The information he provided, including your slave preferences, proved quite useful. Worming my way into the palace and gaining your favor was child's play. Now it is time to end it. Ba'al Verzi sends their regards."

The chains fell to the floor, powerless against his magic. The man flicked his wrist, and the tattoo of a curved dagger on his forearm slid to his hand, becoming a real blade.

The sultan whimpered, shuffling backward until his back hit the wall. He wanted to beg, to promise gold and honors, but the silencing spell held him. He could only watch helplessly as the young man approached, moving with the light grace of a dancer and the deadly precision of an assassin.
  
"Do not worry, sultan. I am not you. I do not make my victims suffer unnecessarily. The end will be swift."

The dagger cut through the air and then the sultan's skin so quickly that the pain reached him only moments later. Warm blood streamed down his neck. Darkness quickly overtook him.

The last thing the sultan saw was a beautiful young man walking toward the window with a spring in his step. The tattoo on his back shimmered and unfurled into a pair of feathery wings. The rays of sunset colored his golden hair russet, like congealed blood.

Aotari looked like an angel. An angel of death who had delivered the sultan's soul to the afterlife.~
@500089 = ~A Page from a Diary~
@500090 = ~A PAGE FROM A DIARY
Weight: 0

*Before you see the light, you must die.*

Page from diary of an anonymous cutter. A forgotten wanderer-warrior, fighting for mystical good.

"*"

With every step, a shadow. Behind them, the undead. They walked, chains and gold bracelets, ornaments from lives of all kinds, clinking against their old bones. What else remains of those days? Now only hatred of life smolders in these skulls. They laugh in my face, evil and macabre.

Supernatural voices gasp around my soul like wind around the ankles of hanged men. But I must go forward to the end.

They are attacking!

"*"

Spark: I will succeed. I will win. One blow opens old wounds, scars of hopelessness and pain. How can something I no longer have still hurt me?

"*"

In these winding corridors, candles thirsty for oxygen twitch before my eyes, doing more to darken my vision than to light the way. I no longer know if this is hallucination, dream, or reality. I see things that should not be here, hear things that no one should know, and feel the familiar touch of someone who is no longer alive. These delusions and deceptions are characteristic of this place, illusions sending greetings from the Abyss. The deeper you go, the more intense they become.

"*"

I have failed. I drag my lifeless feet and write with the last of my strength. There are so many of them here, just like me, defeated ones. They failed, and now their bones and skulls lie here like trophies. Some will join the army that defeated me. Only death is... Even it has failed here.~
@500091 = ~Archon's Sigil~
@500092 = ~Sacred Sigil of Knowing~
@500093 = ~ARCHON'S SIGIL
Weight: 0

This signet ring is undoubtedly valuable. No one goes to such lengths to protect ordinary jewelry. It once rested on a pedestal above the Glass Tarn. What power could it hold?~
@500094 = ~Bone Earring of Ulfbrand Völgarsson Baunaætari~
@500095 = ~BONE EARRING OF ULFBRAND VÖLGARSSON BAUNAÆTARI
Weight: 1

These earrings have a very unique story, if the rumor is to be believed. They once belonged to Ulfbrand when he was still alive. After his death, he somehow returned to find them and reclaim them for his petitioner self. He does not remember how he did it, but the evidence of his deed is now in your hand.

The earrings are made from frost giant bone, which is why they should open the hopping portal to Cania. The frost giant was a distant ancestor of Ulfbrand. The earrings are quite ancient, though admittedly ugly. No serious craftsman could have ever made them.

This is the pair you received before reaching Cania.~
@500096 = ~Archon Seal~
@500097 = ~ARCHON SEAL
Weight: 0

This seal is used to unlock a hidden stash.~
@500098 = ~The Stolen Bone Earring of Ulfbrand Völgarsson Baunaætari~
@500099 = ~THE STOLEN EARRING OF BONE EARRING OF ULFBRAND VÖLGARSSON BAUNAÆTARI
Weight: 1

These earrings have a very unique story, if the rumor is to be believed. They once belonged to Ulfbrand when he was still alive. After his death, he somehow returned to find them and reclaim them for his petitioner self. He does not remember how he did it, but the evidence of his deed is now in your hand.

The earrings are made from frost giant bone, which is why they should open the hopping portal to Cania. The frost giant was a distant ancestor of Ulfbrand. The earrings are quite ancient, though admittedly ugly. No serious craftsman could have ever made them.

This is the pair found in Cania on the body of one of the wererats.~
@500100 = ~"The Promise"~
@500101 = ~"THE PROMISE"
Weight: 1

by Gideon Songblade

"Mommy, did you find me in a flower?"

Arlette's long fingers paused over the silvery strings of her harp. Complete silence, so profound it seemed to echo through the chamber, replaced the beautiful melody. She looked at the little boy who was half-lying on the marble floor among scattered sheets of paper and colorful paints. She had thought Aster was fully absorbed in creating a meadow, but apparently his curious mind had wandered elsewhere.

"Why are you asking, my dear?"

"Because I played with the fairies yesterday, and they told me they are born in flower buds. They even showed me a tree where it happens!"

"Is that so?"

"Yup! Feys don't lie!"

Arlette gave him a warm smile. "Indeed. Fey creatures cannot tell a lie."

"So... did you find me in a flower or not?"

"And what do you think, my dear?"

"I don't know. The flowers on the tree were very small. I don't think I would fit in them."

Arlette tilted her head thoughtfully, letting her golden locks cascade over her ivy-made dress that coiled tightly around her body. If one paid attention to how time worked on the Material Plane, Aster was already six years old. No wonder he was starting to ask questions. Perhaps it was time to answer them.

"No, my dear. I did not find you in a flower. I found you in a crib."

The boy furrowed his brow. He had never heard that word and could not picture its meaning. "What's a crib?"

"It's a bed for very small children. The woman who gave birth to you laid you in one to sleep."

"A woman?" Aster frowned. "Who? Another mommy?"

"No! She brought you into this world, but you belong to me!" Arlette's violet eyes flashed, but the storm of anger quickly passed, leaving only the sweetness of a sunny morning. "That woman came to the forest and prayed to the holy tree for help. I heard her across the Planes and made a pact with her. She agreed to repay my boon with her greatest treasure. I fulfilled my part of the deal, but she did not. She tried to bribe me with worthless gold and trinkets, and then she tried to run. But you cannot outrun a promise. I gave you your true name. You are mine."

Arlette still remembered the stuffy, metallic scent in the room as she stepped barefoot through the puddles of blood from the bodies of the stubborn woman and her husband.

The boy scratched his head, thinking hard. Arlette wondered if it was too much for him or if he even understood what she meant, but Aster pleasantly surprised her. "Was that lady a fey?"

Ah, what a clever child. She could not have asked for a better one. "No, my dear. She was a human."

"So I am a human too, not a fey." He sounded so sad that Arlette knelt in front of him and placed her hand on his cheek.

"You do not have to worry about that, my dear. A few more years in my domain, and the magic of the Faerie Realm will change you irrevocably. You will become one of us. You will be my brave knight, loyal to your queen. You want that, don't you?"

The boy gave her a toothy grin and nodded eagerly. "Yes, Mommy! I will be a fey!"

"Splendid." Arlette kissed the top of his head. "Forget all your worries. Play and have fun, my dear."

She did not have to tell him twice. In high spirits, Aster returned to painting the meadow, humming under his breath the same song his mother had played earlier.

Arlette returned to her harp and let the music flow in perfect harmony with her son.~
