@500104 = ~Marraenoloth's Flute~
@500105 = ~MARRAENOLOTH'S FLUTE
Weight: 1

A flute found next to the frozen corpse of the wererat thief Ratilda. It originally belonged to Wotyrxil, a marraenoloth who awaits its return in Sigil.

The instrument is simple and unadorned, yet it conveys a sense of great value. It is certainly magical, but you do not know how to activate its powers. Perhaps only marraenoloths can use it, as the existence of such instruments is said to be closely tied to them. According to Wotyrxil, they are used for long-distance communication.~
@500106 = ~"The Last Word"~
@500107 = ~"THE LAST WORD"
Damage: 3-18, crushing
Enchanted: +3
Special:
 +1 to Armor Class
 +3 to Electrical Damage
THAC0: +1
Speed: 3
Weight: 5
Proficiency: Hammers
Usable only by Fighters.
Usable only by Good characters.

Linguists know that the word "discussion" comes from phrases meaning "I shatter" or "I strike down." It implies a clash of different views on a matter. Reaching a compromise or consensus often requires strong arguments. Not all arguments are easy to put into words. Logic also suggests that arguments should be presented from weakest to strongest. In the end, the person who has the last word wins. Here it is.

This powerful hammer belonged to the word archon from Mount Celestia. Since the weapon came into your possession, you clearly have more leverage. That alone should be a strong enough argument in your next fight.~
@500108 = ~Frightening Gloves~
@500109 = ~Io's Blood Knuckles~
@500110 = ~FRIGHTENING GLOVES
Damage: 3-18, crushing
Speed: 2
Weight: 5
Proficiency: Fists
Usable only by Fighters and Thieves

These spiked gloves look as if they were lost by a traveler. They appear to have been soaked in blood, and the hardened residue is easily distinguished from the rust one would expect on a piece of metal that has been lying around for an unknown length of time.~
@500111 = ~IO'S BLOOD KNUCKLES
Damage: 3-18, crushing
Enchantment: +3
Special:
 +10 Fire Damage
 +25% Fire Damage Resistance
 +1 Armor Class
Speed: 2
Weight: 5
Proficiency: Fists
Usable only by Fighters and Thieves

IIo's Bloody Isles are not named because they belong to the dragon god, but because they were formed from his blood. According to legend, Io saw strife among the dragon species and declared that if blood had to be spilled, it should be his own. He slashed his belly, and his blood fell to the ground, forming an archipelago.

These unique gloves therefore come from the Prime Material Plane and must have reached the Outer Planes through the multiportal in the Seafarer's Arch. The knuckles appear to be soaked in blood, and the hardened residue can be easily distinguished from the rust one would expect on a piece of metal that has been lying around for an unknown length of time.

What sets them apart from other powerful gloves is their incredible speed. They make it easier to dodge an opponent's blows. In addition, each strike seems to carry a fragment of the dragon god, engulfing the enemy in tongues of flame while making the wearer immune to the effects of this destructive force.~
@500112 = ~Sickle~
@500113 = ~Noonwraith's Sickle~
@500114 = ~SICKLE
Damage: 3-12, slashing
Speed: 2
Weight: 1
Proficiency: Slashing Weapons
Cannot be used by Clerics

The sickle is one of the oldest agricultural tools used for harvesting. It is characterized by a semicircular, strongly curved blade. It is used to harvest grain and grass or to cut straw. In mythology, the sickle is often placed in divine hands, such as those of Demeter or Cronos.~
@500115 = ~NOONWRAITH'S SICKLE
Damage: 3-12, slashing
Enchantment: +3
Special:
 +5 Fire Damage
 +5 to Fire Resistance
Speed: 2
Weight: 1
Proficiency: Slashing Weapons
Cannot be used by Clerics

The sickle is one of the oldest agricultural tools used for harvesting. It is characterized by a semicircular, strongly curved blade. It is used to harvest grain and grass or to cut straw. In mythology, the sickle often appears in divine hands, such as those of Demeter or Cronos.

This particular sickle once belonged to a noonwraith. These undead spirits are said to be women who died before or during their wedding. They may appear as young girls or as old women. They are usually dressed in white and wear wreaths in their hair. They are sometimes depicted carrying sacks and sickles. They are known to ask riddles and can be extremely brutal. In folklore, they are considered the embodiment of sunstroke.

This sickle retains the noonwraith's ability to concentrate sunlight. Because of this, it deals additional fire damage to those who are sensitive to it.~
@500116 = ~Infernal Researcher's Lens~
@500117 = ~INFERNAL RESEARCHER'S LENS
Special:
 +25% Resistance to Cold
 +25% Resistance to Magical Cold
 +25% Resistance to Fire
 +25% Resistance to Magical Fire
 +25% Resistance to Acid
 +15% critical hit chance
 +2 damage
THAC0: + 2
Weight: 0
Can be used only by modrons

This advanced lens combines the beneficial effects of several popular lenses, including "Optix", the Lens of the Horizon, and the Lens of Inherent Viciousness. It also protects the wearer from the harsh conditions of the Nine Hells. Such equipment increases a modron's chances of survival in this deadly environment.~
@500118 = ~Mysterious Scroll~
@500119 = ~MYSTERIOUS SCROLL
Weight: 0

The parchment, tied with a bright pink ribbon, feels strangely sticky to the touch, as if it were coated with a layer of dried mucus. It smells of citrus and musk. You have no idea where it might have been before, and you would probably rather not know. You suspect there are words inside that you might be able to decipher.~
@500120 = ~Call to Battle~
@500121 = ~CALL TO BATTLE
Weight: 0

This set of parchments is ready to be written and sent to the representatives of the factions you expect to support you in battle as soon as possible. You will need to carefully consider who your true allies are and whom you can rely on. It is also important to remember that some factions are hostile toward one another, and bringing their members together may cause more harm than good.~
@500122 = ~Bizarre Book~
@500123 = ~BIZARRE BOOK
Weight: 10

A tome found in the library by the Ditch. It is rather large and heavy, and the cover bears no markings. It seems a bit suspicious...~
@500124 = ~Terrifying Mace~
@500125 = ~Mace of the Doomguard~
@500126 = ~TERRIFYING MACE
Damage: 3-18, crushing
Speed: 2
Weight: 5
Proficiency: Clubs
Unusable by Mages

This club has been reinforced with irregularly protruding spikes. The handle bears a crest that resembles an animal skull.~
@500127 = ~MACE OF THE DOOMGUARD
Damage: 3-18, crushing
Enchanted: +3
Special:
 +10 Magic Damage
 +2 Armor Class
THAC0: +2
Speed: 3
Weight: 5
Proficiency: Clubs
Unusable by Mages
Unusable by Good characters

The Doomguard promote entropy in a practical, though morally questionable, way. Their primary source of income is the arms trade. It is no surprise that their headquarters in Sigil is the Armory in the Lady's Ward. In a multiverse where the Blood War is constant, the demand for weapons is equally constant. One might wonder why this is so, but it is easier to accept it and either ignore it or firmly take a side. The Doomguard, however, have found another approach. They profit from the extremes to which others succumb. For them, increasing entropy is paramount.

This mace has been reinforced with irregularly protruding spikes. The hilt bears the Doomguard crest, an animal skull. The weapon's special properties draw on the destructive powers of the Doomguard's home fields in the Inner Planes: the negative quasiplanes of Ash, Dust, Salt, and Vacuum. This results in additional damage from void and decay, treated as magic damage.~
