This mask, once worn by Sonne, allowed her to appear composed during conversation, even while she was truly churning with emotion inside. It can similarly help you appear more confident and less affected by stress or panic in social interactions. The mask looks unusual, but once worn, it adapts to the wearer's shape.~
@500159 = ~Wanted Notice~
@500160 = ~WANTED NOTICE
Weight: 0

This flyer shows a portrait of what appears to be a young man, though his age is obscured by a multitude of wrinkles and scars. A quick glance reveals the most important information, written in bold letters at the top and bottom of the parchment:

"ADAIRE, ALIAS KESTER, ALIAS SIGIMUNDIS STIG, ALIAS LEONTES, ALIAS CHANCELLEN THE TRUE.
WANTED FOR FRAUD, THEFT, AND MURDER, BY THE ORDER OF THE HARMONIUM."

Below that, fine print details the legal basis for issuing the notice. What unsettles you is how closely the wanted man's portrait resembles you, perhaps from a few years earlier. And all those names, yet none of them seem real. It would be wise not to stand near the poster, just in case, and certainly not in the presence of the Harmonium.~
@500161 = ~Razorvine Garrote~
@500162 = ~RAZORVINE GARROTE
Weight: 0

This gnarly piece of branch looks particularly dangerous. It seems to have been tied by the razorvine blight to tighten around your throat, but you managed to defeat it before that happened. A quick durability test of the noose shows it could indeed sever your throat, and it even made your fingers bleed. Leaving it on the city streets might be socially irresponsible, but are you the type of person who would use it? Part of you feels it might be useful in the future, just in case.

You vaguely remember that some people can use assassination techniques with tools like this. A bit of pressure applied to the victim's back using a foot or knee might kill them or at least cause severe injury. You do not think you need to be a professional assassin to do this, although experience would likely make it more effective. This method, unlike a simple backstab, would certainly complicate any investigation, and you would be long gone.~
@500163 = ~Vagrants' Spit~
@500164 = ~VAGRANTS' SPIT
Weight: 1

Arnil the Bartender

A traveler arrived just as a gullywasher was brewing. One of hundreds alike, dressed similarly as well. A long, heavy coat, not very practical in a spring downpour but invaluable in winter. A hood over his head, sturdy boots, a small bag slung over his shoulder. How similar they all looked.

When he opened the door, a draft blew in, rattling the half-closed window.

The stranger, a clone of many others, stood in the doorway for a moment. The rain poured behind him like some kind of hero in a painting, still and watchful. What a cliché.

I knew I had to play my part to get him to order something from me.

He stepped inside, removed his hood, and unbuttoned his cloak. He looked rather young. He glanced around the room as if searching for something or someone. I hoped he was not looking for a problem. Finally, he looked in my direction and took a step in a very standard pattern straight to the bar. To my heart's content.

As he approached, I noticed his unusual eyes. Pupils so gray they were almost transparent. A Northman, no doubt about it. Close-cropped, dirty blond hair and a few days of stubble. At least he was as young as I first thought.

Routine, here I am.

"What can I get you?" I asked, expecting the usual answer. This fellow certainly could not afford the finest drinks. Judging by his attire, I guessed he would reach for a beer.

"Plain water. As pure as possible."

That was something new. Had he not drunk enough rainwater already?

"Want something to eat?" I asked.
"No need."
"Of course."

Too bad. It was clear I would not make much money from this berk.

"Awful weather, isn't it? It has been pouring like this for about three hours."
"Yeah."
"Where are you headed, if I may ask?" I asked again, handing him the water.
"Far... further than I thought."
"A secret, is it?" I smiled to myself. "Well, that is none of my business."
"I won't be staying long. I am waiting for someone, then I will be on my way."
"I see."

This cutter seemed like someone who knew what he wanted, I guessed.

He sat at a table in the back, placed his cup of water down, and pondered for fifteen minutes without taking a drink. Strange. Finally, the one he had been waiting for arrived. A thin, elderly man, lightly dressed and equally drenched from the rain. Spotting the Northman, he headed straight toward him. Oh no, my dear, you do not sit here without ordering anything. When he sat, I moved to take the order.

"Sir, would you like something?"
"What?" The newcomer cleared his throat. "Oh yes. A beer. That is all."
"At your service."

He seemed richer than I had thought. Well, a beer was enough.

There was nothing to do, so I watched the two of them. At one point, the older man handed the younger one something, a small bag. The Northman poured it into the water and stirred it vigorously. I did not like it. I decided to eavesdrop.

"Did you copy the writing?" the Northman asked.
"And who do you think I am? I promised you, so I did it. It was not that hard. Believe it or not, I had a harder time getting that weed."
"Is that so?"
"Oh yes. 'Vagrants' spit'... harder to get than dragon scales these days. But you are not going to drink that, are you?"
"Why?"
"I have heard all sorts of legends about it."
"What legends? For example?"
"Pottiness. Suffice it to say, unheard-of nonsense. And even something about imminent death."
"Hmm. Here is gold and stones, as we agreed." The younger one pulled a large pouch from his jacket and tossed it on the table.
"Oh, boy. I hope you know what you are doing. And here is the writing, a copy from the Book of the City Closure. Strange name, but what do I know?"
"Strange only if you do not know the rest of it."
"What do you mean?"
"This ancient volume is incomplete, as is its title."
"I know that. Boy, I have been a scribe for thirty years. The title is incomplete because, in the mists of time, someone brazenly ripped it out, destroyed it, or whatever, and there is no mention of it anywhere."
"So, scribe, you know how it is with the word 'nowhere.' Anyway, that is no longer your concern. The writing is legit. I was missing the last two lines. You did what you had to do. Farewell."

The elder man glanced into the purse, rummaged inside, then stood up and left without taking a sip of beer.

Intriguing blighters, I thought. Old volumes, some herb with a ridiculous name. Oh what times, oh what people. I wondered what he would do with all that water and herbs now. I did not need a corpse here. I decided to throw him out.

Suddenly, the traveler rose from the table with a mug in one hand and a parchment in the other and headed toward the exit. Standing at the threshold, he froze and began reading aloud from the card in his hand:

"The dead thirst for the water of life.
How thirsty I am of a way.
Only you, O Lady, understand this pain.
I resort to the all-seeing Powers.
That work of mighty hands.
To see Sigil that gleams far away."

"What a deranged joke!" I shouted.

Then the visitor from the North tipped the cup and drank the entire contents at once.

At first, he stood motionless at the exit. After a moment, blue flames erupted, and a strange, rounded space appeared where the door had been. An orange mist billowed from within. The stranger stepped into it and vanished, leaving only my mug, which rolled across the floor. The few customers present shook their heads in disbelief, probably attributing the disappearance to the alcohol. Some made signs to ward off curses.

Could anyone ever believe me?

I am writing these words down so I do not forget anything.

Since then, every newcomer has seemed to me as something possibly uncanny.~
