////////////
         
@700000 = ~Adam, the Bestest Blacksmith~ 
@700001 = ~Fragile-Tail's Lost Goods~ 
@700002 = ~Kabatum's Planar Miscellanea~ 
@700003 = ~Alviro's Field Infirmary~ 
@700004 = ~Beatha's Abyssal Jewelry~ 
@700005 = ~Wandering Goods~ 
@700006 = ~The Rivergate Tavern~ 
@700007 = ~The Sauna Lounge~ 
@700008 = ~The Ware-Shack~ 
@700009 = ~The Styx Oarsman Tavern~ 
@700010 = ~The Rat and Splat Tavern~ 
@700011 = ~Tavern~ 
@200000 = ~"We shall know what the darkness discovers,"~ [wers1]
@200001 = ~"If the grave-pit be shallow or deep;"~ [wers2]
@200002 = ~"And our fathers of old, and our lovers,"~ [wers3]
@200003 = ~"We shall know if they sleep not or sleep."~ [wers4]
@200004 = ~"We shall see whether hell be not heaven,"~ [wers5]
@200005 = ~"Find out whether tares be not grain,"~ [wers6]
@200006 = ~"And the joys of thee seventy times seven,"~ [wers7]
@200007 = ~"Our Lady of Pain!"~ [wers8]
@200008 = ~"Pike off, berk!"~ 

//////////////////
// ============ //
// Spells, etc.  //
// ============ //
//////////////////

@600001 = ~Black Blessing of Set~
@600002 = ~BLACK BLESSING OF SET
Range: Touch
Duration: 10 seconds
Speed: 1
Area of Effect: Creature touched
Saving Throw: None

Let the aura of Set's power surround us. For a black mana will be sent down, which will grant your bodies and minds a wellspring of power. Do you feel it? Do you have the strength to accept his gifts? Look into the eyes of Set, and it shall be given to you.

The recipient of the spell gains a +1 modifier to attack and saving throws and is under the effect of haste.~
@600003 = ~Set's Prayer~
@600004 = ~SET'S PRAYER
Range: 0
Duration: 5 seconds per level
Speed: 1
Area of Effect: 60 feet radius
Saving Throw: None

Let us pray... Set looks. Set sees. Set knows. Open your heart to His whisper. Let the blood boil in your veins as you go into battle!

Prayer is an important part of every religion. So it is here. Comforted by Set's word, you know that nothing and no one will stand in the way of your bloody goal.

This dark version of the "Prayer" spell grants a +1 modifier to attack rolls, damage rolls, and saving throws for allies. Enemies suffer a −1 modifier to attack rolls, damage rolls, and saving throws. The spell lasts for 5 seconds per level within an 18-yard radius.~
@600005 = ~Reptilian Spit~
@600006 = ~REPTILIAN SPIT
Range: 3 ft.
Duration: 10 seconds
Speed: 4
Area of effect: 1 creature

Reptiles have never been renowned for being overly polite, and sometimes they must vent their bile. Why not on their enemies?

This spell deals 3-24 poison damage.~
@600007 = ~Protection from Cold~
@600008 = ~PROTECTION FROM COLD
Range: Touch
Duration: 5 seconds per level
Speed: 3
Area of Effect: 1 creature
Saving Throw: None

This spell lasts 1 turn per caster level. When cast, it confers complete immunity to normal cold attacks and partial protection against magical cold, such as an icy dragon's breath or spells like Cone of Cold. It absorbs 50% of the damage dealt by such magical sources.~
@600009 = ~Fireball~
@600010 = ~FIREBALL
Range: 40 feet
Duration: Instant
Speed: 3
Area of effect: 15 ft. radius
Saving throw: 1/2

May Kossuth have mercy on those from whom the fires of creation demand the return of their gift of life.

This spell, very popular on the Prime Material Plane, allows the mage to create a heated ball of flame directly in their hands. When launched at an enemy, it bursts into an explosion, harming not only the target but everyone nearby. For this reason, caution is advised when choosing a target.

A single Fireball deals 1-6 points of damage per mage level (maximum 6-60). A successful saving throw reduces the damage by half. The spell is so powerful for its level that history records the archmage Tenser's research into making it less destructive. For power is one thing, and effectiveness another. And fire follows its own rules.~
@600011 = ~Set Trap~
@600012 = ~SET TRAP
Range: Touch
Duration: Instant
Speed: 1
Area of effect: Special

Skilled thieves have mastered the art of creating something from nothing and using it in a variety of ways, whether to evade pursuit or to deal with a much stronger opponent, be it guard or monster. This skill allows them to construct a trap in a chosen location.~
@600013 = ~Thorns of Torment~
@600014 = ~THORNS OF TORMENT
Range: 35 feet
Duration: Instant
Speed: 0
Area of effect: 1 creature

Torment. Sometimes it feels as if this word is *everything*. When the inner abyss, this torn wound of existence, the emptiness of something lost, seems bottomless, all you feel is the pain of torment. Like a beautiful black rose in a deserted garden, when you touch it, you impale yourself on its thorns. Share this pain with others...

This spell deals 3-9 slashing/piercing damage.~
@600015 = ~Fist of Zerthimon~
@600016 = ~FIST OF ZERTHIMON
Range: 6 feet
Duration: 18 seconds
Speed: 0
Area of effect: 1 creature

The opponent suffers penalties to attack and saving throws, a -3 penalty to Armor Class, a -2 penalty to THAC0, and Blindness. The caster receives a +5 damage bonus and takes 1-6 damage upon casting.

"The body is but a vessel, and the fist is judgment. Zerthimon's will flows through my strike."~
@600017 = ~Horrid Wilting~
@600018 = ~HORRID WILTING 
Range: 40 feet
Duration: Instant
Speed: 8
Area of effect: 30 ft. cube
Saving throw: 1/2

This devastating spell, born from the mad imagination of the elementalist necromancer Abi-Dalzim, known as the Father of Droughts, causes all water to evaporate from living creatures within its area of effect. Abi-Dalzim committed many atrocities in the name of Incabulos, the god of disease, drought, and nightmares, but the worst of these was the creation of this destructive spell, which withers all vegetation in the area and vaporizes groundwater.

All living creatures within the area of effect take 1-8 damage per caster level, up to a maximum of 25-200 damage.~
@600019 = ~Disintegrate~
@600020 = ~DISINTEGRATE
Range: 40 feet
Duration: Instant
Speed: 6
Area of effect: 1 creature
Saving throw: Negates

The decomposition of a whole into its fragments. The elimination of integrity. The dissolution into its prime elements. However you describe it, this spell produces the simplest and perhaps most powerful offensive effect that even a child can imagine: the opponent's body explodes spectacularly, leaving behind only dust. The transformation is immediate and irreversible.

This spell can be blocked by magic resistance or appropriate spell protection. While it may not be effective against more powerful enemies, it can easily eliminate weaker ones.~
@600021 = ~Lower Resistance~
@600022 = ~LOWER RESISTANCE
Range: 40 feet
Duration: 5 seconds per level
Speed: 5
Area of effect: 1 creature
Saving throw: None

Some mages cast spells blindly, trusting that one of them will hit. Others, however, prefer a more strategic approach, first lowering the target's resistances to deal more severe damage later.

Casting this spell reduces the target's magic resistance to a minimum. This allows you to completely penetrate the defenses of even the most powerful spellcasters.~
@600023 = ~Wail of the Banshee~
@600024 = ~WAIL OF THE BANSHEE
Range: 0
Duration: Instant
Speed: 9
Area of effect: 15-ft. radius around the caster
Saving throw: Negates

Banshees, meaning "women of the fairy mound," are also known as groaning spirits or wailing ghosts. They are cruel specters, said to have been evil elven women in life. Taking on a misty form, they drain energy from their surroundings, causing the plants beneath them to wither. To the common folk, they are omens of death. To planewalkers, they are a truly deadly threat.

With this terrifying spell, the caster can unleash a piercing scream from their own throat, audible up to 15 feet away. Anyone who hears it dies instantly unless they succeed on a saving throw versus death. The caster and their companions are immune to the wail.~
@600025 = ~Fiendish Transformation~
@600026 = ~FIENDISH TRANSFORMATION

The ability to transform into a fiend can be terrifying for some, but quite manageable or even fun for others. For you, it could prove useful in tricky situations. It might even help scare off a stubborn berk who won't back down. But jokes aside, there are a number of benefits to transforming into a Glabrezu, though it also comes with drawbacks.

Once transformed, you won't be very popular with ordinary mortals. Many will find your appearance abhorrent. You lose the ability to cast spells. You also experience constant anxiety, likely caused by the curse of being a beast, as well as a persistent headache after returning to your normal form. Well, at least you will feel stronger.

Strength +3
Constitution +3
Dexterity +4
Charisma -5
Hit points: +25
Magic resistance: +16

You cannot cast spells while in the form of a fiend.
You are cursed for the duration of the transformation.~
@600027 = ~Humanoid Reversion~
@600028 = ~HUMANOID REVERSION

It's good to be back everywhere, but best of all in your own skin. You have returned to human form. What a hellish transformation that was! That muzzle and that stench! Your head will ache for a long time...

Your stats have returned to their previous values.
You also deactivate spells such as "Aid" and similar effects.~
@600029 = ~Tornado~
@600030 = ~~
@600031 = ~Muspelheim Rune~
@600032 = ~~
@600033 = ~Haste~
@600034 = ~HASTE
Range: 15 feet
Duration: (5 seconds per level) + 15 seconds
Speed: 3
Area of Effect: 15-ft. radius
Saving Throw: None

When cast, all affected creatures double their movement, gain +2 to initiative, and make one extra attack per round. For example, a creature that normally moves 6 and attacks once per round now moves 12 and attacks twice per round.

The spell affects all allied creatures within a 15-ft. radius centered on a point chosen by the caster at the moment of casting. Creatures leaving the area remain affected, while those entering after casting are not.

This spell does not stack with itself or similar magic. Spellcasting and other effects are unaffected. This spell also negates the effects of a Slow spell.~
@600035 = ~"Robe of the Vanquished"~
@600036 = ~Mimir's Babble~
@600037 = ~MIMIR'S BABBLE
Range: 120 feet
Duration: (1 second per level) + 10 seconds
Speed: 3
Area of effect: Up to 60 square feet
Saving throw: Negates

Morte sometimes claimed to be a mimir. Mimirs are talking metallic skulls that vary in appearance depending on their creator's wishes. They can resemble human or animal skulls, but they may also take the form of discs, cubes, leaves, seeds, butterflies, and many other shapes. They follow their owner and answer questions, provided they can float in air or water.

Their obscure origins are sometimes attributed to Mímisbrunnr, the Well of Mimir in Ysgard, said to grant infinite knowledge for a price. Does Morte have anything to do with Ysgard? Doubtful. Could he be identified with the flying encyclopedias available in Sigil and the gate-towns for 2,000 copper coins? Certainly not. Yet that lie took on a life of its own, and if one truly believed Morte could be a mimir, why could he not bombard his opponents with useless tidbits the way he does with curses?

This skill works similarly to the "Confusion" spell: 1-4 creatures plus 1 additional creature per level become confused and unsure of themselves. Affected creatures will either:
1) Wander away
2) Stand confused
3) Attack the nearest creature
4) Act normally~

//////////////
// ======== //
// Bestiary //
// ======== //
//////////////

         
@800001 = ~Prod is an imp who works with Tergush'tekhn and the fiends from the Smoldering Corpse Bar.

His skin is grayish, and his his hunched, scrawny frame does not intimidate anyone. The membranes of his bat-like wings have probably seen better days. Some of the holes look fresh and are likely the work of Joseph and his men. Prod does not seem bothered by this, and you do not know whether his wings will heal. Nevertheless, the imp radiates enthusiasm for the upcoming journey.~
@800002 = ~Goodness, virtue, and love are pure concepts guarded by word archons. Their wings are clouds of parchment pages that swirl swiftly around them. They take pride in their supernal intelligence, and their glowing bronze skin is more flawless than any human could imagine. They dwell on Mount Celestia, though they may also be encountered in Oghma's House of Knowledge in the Outlands.

As celestials, they are the natural counterparts and antithesis of fiends, beings of good from the Upper Planes who stand opposed to the evils of the Lower Planes. Yet their understanding of goodness differs from mortal morality. It can lead them to acts so decisive they verge on heartlessness, and to ethical paradoxes so strange that the question of what constitutes pure good remains unsettled.

Word archons have a particular reverence for Truespeech and True Names. For this reason, their natural enemies are logokrons and garblers, who defile the purity of Truespeech. They travel the planes seeking to inspire virtuous creatures and preserve pure concepts from corruption. In battle, they unleash potent utterances that strike their foes like shock waves. Then they follow with blows from their holy warhammers, all while weaving words of power that make it difficult for their opponents to retaliate. Behold the power of Truespeech.~
@800003 = ~A half-giant einheri from Ysgard, he leads a band of the Fated and reports directly to Rowan Darkwood. Known as the son of Völgar and by such titles as Battle Wolf, he believes without hesitation that whatever he can take is rightfully his. He is not someone to be taken lightly. His faithful companion is a wolf named Sharikira.~
@800004 = ~Slaadi, or slaads, are frog-like natives of Limbo. Having emerged from the primordial soup, they embody the pure chaos of the planes. Like fiends, they fight in the Blood War. They appear unpredictably in disorganized bands, choose sides as it suits them, and eventually gather whatever loot they can. The color of their skin indicates their status and power. Their hierarchy is as follows: mud, red, blue, green, gray, death, white, and black.

Their method of reproduction is particularly strange and resembles parasitism. After mating at the Spawning Stone, the cradle of their race, slaadi produce fertilized eggs that must be implanted into living hosts. Infected victims fall ill with chaos phage, also known as slaad fever, after a slaad injects them with its eggs. After a few days, a tadpole bursts from the corpse, destined to become a red slaad or, if the victim possessed magical abilities, a green one.

An intriguing theory suggests that the slaadi are proof of the existence of alternate realities, claiming that they originate from such realms and are the only beings capable of perceiving and remembering them. Most scholars dismiss this theory as absurd.~
@800005 = ~Mimics are bizarre monstrosities that rely on mimesis as a hunting strategy, camouflaging themselves to match their surroundings while they wait for unsuspecting prey. Although they are most commonly associated with chests, records show that mimics can also assume the shapes of doors, books, and other objects. The texture of their skin closely replicates common materials such as wood, stone, and metal, though their natural coloration resembles gray granite.

There have been only a few documented cases of mimics capable of communication. The vast majority are driven solely by survival and the need to feed. They can sense heat from up to 90 feet away and sometimes share territory with other predators.

Book mimics are said to have been bred by the Church of Oghma to safeguard valuable tomes.~
@800006 = ~Mariliths are the generals and master tacticians of the Abyssal hordes of tanar'ri. They resemble serpentine creatures akin to nagas, but their upper bodies are those of warrior women with three pairs of arms, each capable of wielding a separate blade, often taken from a fallen foe. Their tails can reach up to twenty feet in length.

As the ever-insightful slaad scholar Xanxost once said, "Mariliths prove that chaotic beings do not have to be stupid." Their true talent lies in the planning and execution of warfare. They can weave illusions and charm their enemies, combining brute force with calculated strategy.

They harbor a particular disdain for glabrezus, who favor temptation and manipulation, methods the mariliths consider limited compared to their own broader mastery of war.~
@800007 = ~Insectoid baatezu resembling giant cockroaches are the elite torturers of Baator. These horrid tormentors have mastered the art of torture, keeping their victims alive long enough that they begin to yearn for death. Like ordinary cockroaches, these fiends have six long limbs tipped with claws, which they manipulate with surprising precision to wield various tools, usually with terrifying and painful effect.

They are intelligent, sadistic, and capable of using spell-like abilities as well as summoning other kocrachons. They prefer tormenting helpless victims and are generally reluctant to engage in direct combat. It is said that they sometimes exchange the body parts of their victims to night hags in return for souls.~
@800008 = ~Yagnoloths, also known as yagnodaemons, are considered the nobles among lesser yugoloths, dwelling in Gehenna and the Gray Wastes. Their primary role is to draw up contracts, though, according to the archmage Mordenkainen, they do not always honor their own agreements. With their monstrously large hands, sometimes measuring 10 to 15 feet, they are more than capable of enforcing their will.

Theories about their origin suggest cross-mutation or a connection to giants. Considering their formidable power, it is frightening to imagine the might of their superiors, the greater yugoloths.~
@800009 = ~Marraenoloths, also known as charondaemons or the In-Between, are the highest-ranking lesser yugoloths. Their task is to pilot the boats that sail the River Styx. They serve an altraloth named Charon, who ferries souls down the river for a steep price.

Marraenoloths are short, skeletal humanoids dressed in old, decayed burial robes. In the darkness, their flashing red eyes can be seen. They demonstrate their special abilities more in support of their work than in direct combat. They can control any boat, walk on water, and breathe underwater. They are capable of controlling the weather and charming opponents. They also maintain constant contact with their kin and can summon hydroloths and other marraenoloths to their aid. It is no surprise that they easily inspire fear.~
@800010 = ~Bladelings are a race from Acheron similar to humans, but their skin resembles frosted metal. Their eyes are purple and glitter like ice. They are known for their xenophobia and superstition, and they are eager to fight and fearless in battle. They use weapons in combat. In their early history, they were nearly wiped out by rust dragons, but through magical experiments they made themselves immune to corrosion. Their spikes are also used as alchemical components.~
@800011 = ~The planes hold many wonders, and anything is possible. Kabatum is a concordant killer, descended from both a fiend and a celestial. Such creatures, originating from the Outer Planes but claiming none as their home, are primarily hostile to opponents of extreme alignments. Kabatum himself is known as the Summoner and has commanded many kinds of creatures across the planes. He is extremely dangerous in combat, yet for some reason he has chosen to make his home in the Ditch.~
@800012 = ~Slimes are amorphous creatures composed mainly of acids that allow them to digest their prey. They lurk on ceilings, walls, and beneath floors, emerging when they sense vibrations caused by passing creatures. They are often the result of magical experiments and are rarely encountered outside dungeons and basements. In these environments, they act as a form of cleaner, disposing of leftover matter. Green slimes are the most common, but they sometimes appear in other colors such as ochre, mustard, or gray, gaining new properties. All slimes are characterized by high resistance to various types of damage.~
@800013 = ~In Molikroth's court, there is a half-elven alu-fiend named Antilia the High Cantor. She openly opposes the Baron, yet he inexplicably ignores her venomous mischief. Perhaps her talent as a bard plays a role, as her songs can be heard throughout the court halls between meetings. Rumors say that she is the daughter of an infernal archduke and a powerful elven queen who turned to hellish powers and became their cleric. Most of these rumors are difficult to verify, except for one: she is unearthly beautiful.~
@800014 = ~This tiefling bard is from Sigil. For Haer'Dalis, his dual affiliations are important. Artistically, he belongs to the Sigil theater troupe of Lady Raelis Shai, alongside fellow planetouched. Ideologically, he aligns with the Doomguard, which is why he believes in the inevitable decay of all things, only to make way for the new. His speech is distinctive and full of flowery terms, and he often compares the people he knows to birds. Despite his acting talent and penchant for metaphor, he comes across as sincere and straightforward in his intentions.~
@800015 = ~Cania, the eighth layer of Baator, is home to insectoid gelugons, also known as ice devils. They are merciless commanders in the Blood War, unafraid to sacrifice their units to achieve victory. They stand ten to twelve feet tall and weigh over 700 pounds. Their tails end in spikes, and their complex eyes and antennae can detect every movement.

Gelugons are savage warriors who covet the power held by pit fiends, yet they remain loyal in obtaining souls for their masters. They can slow opponents with numbing cold and create walls of ice. They command numerous legions of devils ready to carry out their orders. Historically, they were enslaved by Mephistopheles long ago. The portal to Nessus, the final layer of Baator, is guarded by 9,999 gelugons.~
@800016 = ~Alviro is a deva from the Golden Heaven of Mercuria, the second layer of Mt. Celestia. He is a minor representative of the aasimon family, also known as angels. He seeks to spread order and peace wherever he can, tending to those in need in the Ditch. He heals wounds and illnesses and also provides cleansing. He willingly offers his aid to the poor.~
@800017 = ~Artists create legends, and legends legitimize what artists do, at least most of the time. Akershus is a composer and performer known throughout the Cage and the Outlands. He has just returned from a tour of the gate-towns and is preparing to compose a new masterpiece. He bears a tattoo made by a bladeling artist from Rigus, a complex pattern of razorvine. On closer inspection, it reveals a clever depiction of a scene hidden within the shadows and shapes between the vines. The image shows buildings under attack from razorvine and some bulbous monsters resembling the plant.~
@800018 = ~Kuo-toa, also known as men-fish, are a piscine race that originated in the the Torilian Underdark. They prefer aquatic environments and underground caves. They are shorter than adult humans and smell of rotten fish. They have mastered the crafting of tools and weapons, which they readily use for hunting. Nets, harpoons, and pincers are their primary means of capturing prey. Kuo-toa have a defined hierarchy with monks called monitors maintaining order alongside priests. They primarily worship the mysterious Blibdoolpoolp, but sometimes also venerate sea monsters such as krakens or other deities like Shar, Bhaal, or Demogorgon, simplifying the names so they can pronounce them.~
@800019 = ~Among the yugoloths, many monsters inspire fear, yet the over-eight-foot-tall baernaloths are the most ancient, and their true nature remains a mystery to scholars. The baernaloths' obsession is with ancient secrets. They are said to conduct experiments on a massive scale and even interfere with reality itself. They may have created demodands in Carceri, and perhaps even devils and demons. They are an emotionless, colorless enigma. Their large heads resemble the horned skulls of cattle or rams, and their glassy eyes leak a yellow fluid. They do not use weapons, relying instead on their cruel natural abilities. They live as hermits, having rejected yugoloth society and emigrated to Gehenna. They usually choose solitude, though sometimes their companions are night hags and nightmares.

"I do not exaggerate, nor am I a braggart. I saw the powers that now live aborning, and the powers before them as well."
— Daru Ib Shaitiiq~
@800020 = ~This redheaded tiefling bard is the leader of the Sigil actors' troupe, which includes another tiefling named Haer'Dalis, the dwarf mage Kirinaldo, the elf mage Lunisia, and Biff the Understudy. She is a confident woman who excels at connecting with audiences. She is also known for her honesty, often refunding dissatisfied audience members if she feels her actors were not fully prepared to deliver a satisfactory performance.~
@800021 = ~The situation of children in Sigil depends largely on their parents' wages. In poorer wards, such as the Hive, children often have to start earning money early. They are put into jobs where their small size is useful, such as chimney cleaning or maintaining streetlights, but sometimes they are forced to work beyond their strength in factories or as collectors. In worse cases, they end up in criminal gangs and exploit careless Primes. Some, however, are fortunate enough to find work as couriers, touts, or sellers of newsrags like S.I.G.I.S. (Sigil's Global Information Service).

The factions are familiar with the problem of idle children, and they sometimes run schools. However, it is clear that these schools engage in intense indoctrination, imposing the faction's beliefs on the pupils and deepening societal divisions over time. Sigil is not a place where happy children are often seen. The Ditch offers a rare opportunity for joy when a shipment of clean water from the River Oceanus arrives every five to eight months. This event becomes a major celebration in which entire families take part.~
@800022 = ~Mezzoloths are a common, insectoid variety of yugoloths. They may have once been a different, non-fiend race, kidnapped from their home plane and adapted by higher-ranking daemons such as ultroloths and arcanaloths to serve cruel designs. This transformation was likely not difficult, as mezzoloths have limited intelligence. Nonetheless, they possess a natural talent for magic, a fondness for enchanted objects, and telepathic abilities used for communication. In combat, they wield tridents and, when necessary, their claws. Their insect-like mandibles are incredibly strong, able to cut through most non-magical materials even without weapons. Like insects, they are rarely found alone, and their tough chitinous armor provides resistance to most external attacks.

Mezzoloths are not eager to fight as mercenaries in the Blood War. They often wander the Lower Planes, seeking creatures to torture, usually preying on lemures. If confronted, take precautions against burns and avoid letting them teleport too far when they trap you in a confined space. They can quickly envelop opponents in a cloud of toxic fumes.~
@800023 = ~Among Lothar's servants, one of the most powerful is a stone golem that resembles an enormous ghoul. This eldritch creature, with sharp claws and a black tongue as bright and gleaming as obsidian, is driven by a strange fire in place of a heart. It is said that this fire will burn for as long as the Master of the Bones lives.

It is therefore safe to assume that the golem will continue to hunt thieves and those who fail to show respect to the fearsome mage for a very long time.~
@800024 = ~Monodrones are the lowest-ranking spherical constructs in the modron hierarchy, each possessing a single eye, a pair of legs, arms, and wings. They are capable of communication, but their vocabulary is limited to no more than 48 words. They perform only one task at a time and cannot be persuaded to disobey their orders. Only the duodron to whom they are subordinate can recall them.

Monodrones generally cannot comprehend the more advanced modrons with their minds. Their population, numbering around three hundred million, is replenished in the Great Modron Cathedral by Primus whenever it fluctuates. They regularly depart from Mechanus on the Great Modron March through the planes. Separation from the Source can have disastrous and unpredictable consequences.~

///////////
// ===== //
// Films //
// ===== //
///////////

@1000000 = ~"P a t c h"~
@1000001 = ~WORSHIP \n\nBelief is one of the fundamental forces that shapes the planes. There are dozens of pantheons and hundreds of powers worshiped by their inhabitants.~
@1000002 = ~Current worship: Kiaransalee\n(Lady of the Dead, The Revenancer, The Vengeful Banshee, or The Pitiless Dowager) \n\nA Chaotic Evil deity of undeath and vengeance, she is a member of the drow pantheon, the Dark Seldarine. Her divine realm is situated in Thanatos, in the Abyss.\nHer mission is to extinguish all life in the planes so that there can be peace and equality forever.~

